Decoding Health with Data Science and Machine Learning

Date Thu 15 February 2018 By Brian Griner, Ph.D. Category posts. Tags Python Data Science Machine Learning Deep Learning Statistical Learning Biostatistics Diabetes Health Policy

Decoding Health with Data Science and Machine Learning¶

Examining Risk Factors Associated with Early Onset Type 2 Diabetes Among Pima Indian Women

by Brian Griner

Source: wikimedia

Motivation¶

According to the American Diabetes Association, the total cost of diabetes in 2012 was 245 billion. Of that, direct medical costs totaled 176 billion, and productivity losses associated with the disease were estimated at 69 billion (DIABETES CARE, VOLUME 36, APRIL 2013). In a recent study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association, Diabetes was ranked the highest of all conditions in personal healthcare spending. The study estimated the analyzed growth rate of Diabetes spending over the years from 1996 to 2013 at 6% (JAMA December 27, 2016 Volume 316, Number 24). The Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) state that Diabetes is the leading cause of kidney failure, nontramatic limb amputation, and new cases of blindness in US adults. It is also a major cause of heart disease and stoke and is the 7th leading cause of death in the US (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. National diabetes fact sheet: national estimates and general information on diabetes and prediabetes in the United States, 2011. Atlanta, GA: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 2011).

As these statistic show, Diabetes is a significant public health problem that warrants immediate attention from both the public and private sectors. While there are many medical studies on Diabetes care and management, the annual rate of Diabetes continues to increase as does the cost of diabetes care. Practical solutions to control this disease are needed to increase the quality and reduce the cost of diabetes care.

The primary questions raised in this post are:

  1. Can data science increase our understanding of the risk factors associated with Diabetes?
  2. What are the key insights for Diabetes patients and their care givers?
  3. Can theses insights point to practical solutions to reduce Diabetes risks, lower the financial burden, and increase the quality of life for Diabetes patients?

The Pima Indians of Arizona have been the subject of many medical studies over the years because of their high prevalence of diabetes and pre-diabetes. The National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases (NIDDKD) sponors an ongoing clinical trial studying pre-diabetes that began in June 2006. Cross-Sectional and Longitudinal Studies of "Pre-Diabetes" in the Pima Indians.

A review of the medical literature of diabetes risk factors from studies of the Pima Indians surfaced an ongoing debate surrounding the question of "nature vs. nuture" in determining the primary risk factors leading to diabetes. This has implications for public health policy in terms of who pays for diabetes management and care and the extent to which it can be prevented through behavioral changes (see links below for some examples). While a detailed discussion of who pays for care and why is out of scope for this research, practical solutions that help patients help themselves is not and should be part of the options considered to address the problem.

Data¶

Pima Indians Diabetes Data

The Pima Indians Diabetes dataset used in this study was obtained from the UCI ML Repository, Lichman, M. (2013). UCI Machine Learning Repository [http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml]. Irvine, CA: University of California, School of Information and Computer Science.

A description of attributes in the Pima Indians Diabetes dataset from the UCI ML repository is provided below.

Study Population: Data Set Information: Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients here are females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.

Attribute Information & Criteria Used in Diagnosis*

  1. preg: Number of times pregnant
  2. gluc: Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test - Pre Diabetes: 140-199ml/dl
  3. dbp: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg) - Metabolic Syndrome criteria > 85 mm Hg
  4. skin: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm) - female obese (21 years and older) >= 27 mm
  5. insul: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) - female norm: NA - overall 16-166 mIU/L
  6. bmi: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) - overweight (25 to 29.9), obese (BMI >= 30)
  7. pedi: Diabetes pedigree function
  8. age: Age (years)
  9. class: Class variable (0 or 1) = False/True for onset of diabetes in 1-5 years

* Diagnosis Criteria for Pre Diabetes with links to source provided where available.

UPDATE from UCI Repository: "Until 02/28/2011 this web page indicated that there were no missing values in the dataset. As pointed out by a repository user, this cannot be true: there are zeros in places where they are biologically impossible, such as the blood pressure attribute. It seems very likely that zero values encode missing data. However, since the dataset donors made no such statement we encourage you to use your best judgement and state your assumptions."

Methodology¶

Initially, this data was used in research sponsored by Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine to test the performance of the ADAP neural network whose architecture was specifically designed to predict pre-diabetes. ADAP is an adaptive learning routine that generates and executes digital analogs of perceptron-like devices. The difference between the ADAP architecture and the standard multi layer perceptron (MLP) is the structure it imposes on the inputs and their connections to the hidden layer nodes.

In brief, the ADAP partitions inputs into range categories much like a classification and regression tree (CART). All inputs are connected association units which aggregate and weight the partitions connected to the output node. Only one partition at time is connected to an association unit. This clever architecture imposes a pseudo experimental design with randomized factors and levels during training. This approach should produce clear benefits when analyzing observational data.

Next, each association unit is connected to the output nodes with a weight that is updated during training. The ADAP network learns on a case by case basis. For each case in the training sample, only a subset between 2 and 10 percent of the association units are activated. In this respect, the ADAP is similar to a MLP using rectified linear units (RELU)) in the hidden layers and L1 norm regularization for hyperparameter tuning to reduce overfitting.

ADAP is a unique algorithm that links domain knowledge to neural network architecture; see link to paper below for more details.

Smith, J.W., Everhart, J.E., Dickson, W.C., Knowler, W.C., & Johannes, R.S. (1988). Using the ADAP learning algorithm to forecast the onset of diabetes mellitus. In Proceedings of the Symposium on Computer Applications and Medical Care, (pp. 261--265). IEEE Computer Society Press. Web Link

Descriptive and Summary Statistics¶

The first step in any ML analysis is to examine the data using summary statistics. This provides hints to at least two important issues that can impact the quality of the analysis:

  1. Data quality issues: e.g., outliers and missing values can change the relationship between model outputs and inputs
  2. Distributions of inputs - ML algorithms are often more predictive when the inputs are standardized.

Conclusion¶

The percentage of Prediabetes cases is 35% which should provide enough cases for a good classification model. Zero values in diastolic BP, skin fold thickness, 2 hour serum insulin, and BMI are not biologically possible and represent missing values. Examining the 25% percentile of these attritubes reveal that skin fold thickness and 2 hr serum insulin have at least 25% of the measurements missing which can reduce the predictive power of the model and produce insights on risk factors that may be misleading. Given the importance of insulin levels and local obesity measures like tricep skin fold thickness in predicting Diabetes, models for imputation to predict missing values for these measures will be explored below.

The skew statistics show negative skew for diastolic blood pressure and positive skew for serum insulin, pedigree, age, and the ratio of insulin to glucose. Large positive and negative skew statistics imply that standardization of these attributes should be performed to improve model accuracy.

Finally, a cross tabulation of the inputs against pre diabetes class show meaningful differences in the mean values and should be good predictors of pre diabetes; however, zero coded missing values can artificially create these difference in the means, especially in tricep skin fold thickness and serum insulin levels where are a large proportion of missing values. This will be checked during the imputation modeling step.

Conclusion¶

The histograms and density plots clearly show the impact of zero coding of missing values on skin fold thickness and 2 hour serium insulin levels with there dramatic spike at zero. The density plot of tricep skin fold thickness shows how zero coding makes the distribution look bi-modal when one of the modes is just an artifact of how missing values were coded as numbers. The zero coding missing would clearly violate the distributional assumptions of a t test on tricep skin fold thickness.

Diabetes At Risk Cases¶

In this analysis, we use the guidelines for diagnosing pre diabetes to define the at risk population in the sample (i.e., those cases in the sample that meet the criteria for pre diabetes or metabolic syndrome).

Using inspiration from the ADAP neural network architecture, we partition each input into discrete factors or sensors that determine if a case is at risk on a particular factor or not. Combinations of these discrete factors form a design matrix used to identify subpopulations within the sample with varying degrees of risk for pre diabetes.

Conclusion¶

First we see that in general, pre diabetes risk is two thirds higher for Pima Indian women who are 30 years old or older with no other risk factors. Of the women 30 years or older, the risk of pre diabetes doubles with elevated glucose levels and is close to double when high glucose levels are combined with high tricep skin fold thickness.

In women younger than 30, the baseline risk is almost half of the older women. However, the risk in younger women increases by over two thirds with elevated glucose levels and even higher when elevated glucose is combined with high tricep skin fold thickness.

Insight: In both age groups, women with elevated glucose levels are at high risk to develop pre diabetes.

Next we examine genetic predisposition for diabetes along with glucose and insulin level in both older and younger women.

Conclusion

Diastolic blood pressure has a complex relationship with other pre diabetes risk factors, showing a cascade effect on risk when combined with high tricep skin fold thickness and elevated insulin levels. In older women the combination of high diastolic blood pressure and tricep skin fold thickness and elevated insulin levels more than doubles the risk of pre diabetes.

In younger women, elevated diastolic blood pressure or high tricep skin fold thickness increases the risk of pre diabetes by 81 percent and 67 percent respectively. However, when high tricep skin fold thickness is combined with elevated insulin levels or high diastolic blood pressure, the risk of pre diabetes triples.

**_Insight: high blood pressure is a significant risk factor for developing pre diabetes in women, especially younger women with a high tricep skin fold thickness.

Metabolic syndrome*¶

In this section we introduce a related condition, metabolic syndrome*. Metabolic syndrome is a cluster of symptoms involving abdominal obesity, hypertension, elevated glucose and cholesterol levels. Mexican ancentry is also a known risk factor for the onset of diabetes which makes this topic of particular interest for studying diabetes risks in the Pima Indians. Therefore I am computing the insulin to glucose ratio adapted from the article, C P Lucas, J A Estigarribia, L L Darga and G M Reaven Hypertension. Insulin and blood pressure in obesity. 1985;7:702-706, originally published September 1, 1985. The article showed a relationship between the ratio of insulin to glucose levels and diastolic blood pressure. The interaction of ratio, BMI or skin fold thickness could imply the prescence of metabolic syndrome which could increase the risk of Pre Diabetes.

Imputation of Missing Values*¶

Imputation of missing values is an accepted concept in healthcare research, especially with clinical trial data. See Ayele TA, Lipkovich I, Molenberghs G, Mallinckrodt CH. A Multiple-Imputation-Based Approach to Sensitivity Analyses and Effectiveness Assessments in Longitudinal Clinical Trials. Journal of Biopharmaceutical Statistics. 2014;24(2):211-228.

Machine Learning algorithms can be very useful for predicting missing values in data. Given the potential importance of insulin levels and skin fold thickness as risk factors for Pre Diabetes, I will attempt to create regression models to predict the missing values of skin fold thickness and insulin levels using ensemble methods. Given the low percentage of missing in plasma glucose, diastolic blood pressure, and BMI I will use a univariate strategy for imputation such as using the mean, median, or mode of the attribute.

*For a great introduction to this topic see Jason Brownlee. How to Handle Missing Data with Python. Machine Learning Mastery. March 20, 2017

To see how machine learning is used in biostatistics and observational research, see Zagar AJ, Lipkovich I, Faries DE. Evaluating different strategies for estimating treatment effects in observational studies. Journal of Biopharmaceutical Statistics. 2017;27(3):535-553.

For a detailed exposition on ensemble learning see Hastie T, Tibshirani R, Friedman J. Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. 2nd edition. New York (NY): Springer-Verlag; 2009. Chapter 16, Ensemble Learning; p. 605-624.

Conclusion:

Our mean imputation using Scikit-Learn's Imputer gives us a baseline validation accuracy of 77 percent using a simple Linear Discriminant Analysis to predict Pre Diabetes. Using the XGBoost (eXtreme Gradient Boosting) model the validation sample accuracy jumps to 81 percent using the mean imputation dataset.

We will now investigate model-based imputation on the attributes with the largest number of missing values. Model-based imputation may or may not result in higher predictive accuracy but should provide more information about the underlying risk factors for Pre Diabetes which is the goal of this analysis.

Machine Learning Imputation Models*¶

To maximize information regarding the joint distribution of Pre Diabetes risk factors, all cases with missing values are removed from the training and validation samples. The underlying assumption for removing cases with missing values is that these measurements are Missing At Random, i.e., the distributions in the new sample will be similar to the original sample. This will be checked.

For this analysis, the focus is the two attributes that have the greatest number of missing values: tricep skin fold thickness and 2 hour serum insulin level. First we model skin fold thickness and then model insulin levels. The goal is to find the best model among an ensemble of models for imputing missing values in each attribute.

*For more information on setting up ensembles in Python see Jason Brownlee. Ensemble Machine Learning Algorithms in Python with scikit-learn. Machine Learning Mastery. June 3, 2016

Skin Fold Thickness Imputation Model¶

We begin with the imputation model for tricept skin fold thickness. The approach taken for imputation is outlined below:

  1. TRAINING DATA: Remove missing values to maximize the quality of the data used to create the model.
  2. SCORING DATA: Impute missing values on the full dataset prior to deploying the imputation model
  3. TRANSFORMATION OF INPUTS: Most ML algorithm perform better when the input data is standardized. If modeling counts, try taking the log(x+1) prior to standardization (to unlog - exp(ln(x+1))-1)
  4. MODEL TRAINING: & TESTING: It is difficult to know which algorithm will perform best on any given dataset. Therefore, it is good practice to test several different ML algorithms on your data first.
  5. MODEL TESTING: ML algorithms should always be checked using a holdout or validation sample. It is even better to do this multiple times using Cross Validation (i.e., partition data into 5 folds. Use 1-4 to predict 5 then 1-3,5 to predict 4, etc.)
  6. MODEL TUNING: Once an algorithm is selected, the hyper parameters can be optimized using a grid search.
  7. SAVE FINAL MODEL: Once a final model has been selected, use Python's 'pickle' or sklearn's 'joblib' to save the model for imputation.
  8. IMPUTATION: a. Load saved model, b. Generate predicted values, c. Create new column with predicted values in dataset, d. Replace missings with predicted values.

We start with the model of tricep skin fold thickness.

Conclusion:

Of the individual models evaluated the Lasso Regression performed the best on both unstandardized and standardized data based on the Mean Squared Error (MSE) criteria. Of the ensemble algorithms, the AdaBoost model had the lowest MSE and prediction error; however, the Gradiant Boosting Machine (GBM) had the tightest range for the error distribution and was selected as the final model for imputation of skin fold thickness.

The distribution of tricep skin fold thickness is less skewed after imputation but can we do better by taking the log first?

Conclusion:

Of the individual models evaluated the Linear Regression performed the best on the log transformed output using both unstandardized and standardized data according to the Mean Squared Error (MSE) criteria.

Of the ensemble algorithms, the AdaBoost model had the lowest MSE and prediction error; however, the Gradiant Boosting Machine (GBM) had the tightest range for the error distribution and was selected as the final model for imputation of skin fold thickness.

The graph of the imputed tricep skin fold thickness after the log transformation shows a more normalized plot. This should help when interpreting the risk factors later.

Partial Dependency Plots for Identifying Pre Diabetes Risk Factors*¶

To examine the relative importance of different risk factors in Pre Diabetes I will use an additive Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM). Gradient Boosting Machines and its ensemble form eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) are one of the most power learning ideas in machine learning.* The learning concept behind boosting and additive trees is to combine a set of weaker models into a committee of experts. GBM is a sequence of simple models that are weighted and summed together to form the committee of experts for prediction. Each model in the GBM sequence is tasked with predicting the error of the model that preceeds it.

To understand the influence of each attribute in a GBM requires graphing the predicted values with each attribute individually while averaging out the effects of the other attributes. This graph is called a partial dependence plot.

*For a full explanation of interpretation of Partial Dependence Plots in Boosting and Additive Trees see Hastie T, Tibshirani R, Friedman J. Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction. 2nd edition. New York (NY): Springer-Verlag; 2009. Chapter 10.13.2, Partial Dependence Plots; p. 369-384.

Code reference for partial dependence plots.

from pandas import read_csv, DataFrame
import numpy as np
filename = "ln_skin_ln_insulin_imp_data.csv"
names = ['preg', 'gluc', 'dbp', 'skin', 'insul', 'bmi', 'pedi', 'age', 'class']
dataset = read_csv(filename, names=names)
# Compute ratio of insulin to glucose 
dataset['ratio'] = dataset['insul']/dataset['gluc']

from __future__ import print_function
print(__doc__)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from time import time

from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble.partial_dependence import plot_partial_dependence
from sklearn.ensemble.partial_dependence import partial_dependence

# split dataset into inputs and outputs
values = dataset.values
X = values[:,0:8]
print(X.shape)
y = values[:,8]
#print(y.shape)

def main():

    # split 80/20 train-test
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,
                                                        y,
                                                        test_size=0.20,
                                                        random_state=1)
    names = ['preg', 'gluc', 'dbp', 'skin', 'insul', 'bmi', 'pedi', 'age']

    print("Training GBRT...")
    clf = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=4,
                                    learning_rate=0.1, loss='deviance',
                                     random_state=1)
    t0 = time()
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print(" done.")
    
    print("done in %0.3fs" % (time() - t0))
    importances = clf.feature_importances_
    
    print(importances)

    #print('Convenience plot with ``partial_dependence_plots``')

    features = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, (4,6)]
    fig, axs = plot_partial_dependence(clf, X_train, features,
                                       feature_names=names,
                                       n_jobs=3, grid_resolution=50)
    #fig.suptitle('Partial dependence plots of Pre Diabetes on risk factors')
            
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.1, right=1.1, top=1.4)  # tight_layout causes overlap with suptitle

    
    print('Custom 3d plot via ``partial_dependence``')
    fig = plt.figure()

    target_feature = (4, 6)
    pdp, axes = partial_dependence(clf, target_feature,
                                   X=X_train, grid_resolution=50)
    XX, YY = np.meshgrid(axes[0], axes[1])
    Z = pdp[0].reshape(list(map(np.size, axes))).T
    ax = Axes3D(fig)
    surf = ax.plot_surface(XX, YY, Z, rstride=1, cstride=1,
                           cmap=plt.cm.BuPu, edgecolor='k')
    ax.set_xlabel(names[target_feature[0]])
    ax.set_ylabel(names[target_feature[1]])
    ax.set_zlabel('Partial dependence')
    #  pretty init view
    ax.view_init(elev=22, azim=142)
    plt.colorbar(surf)
    plt.suptitle('Partial dependence of Pre Diabetes risk factors')
                 
    plt.subplots_adjust(right=1,top=.9)

    plt.show()
    
    # Needed on Windows because plot_partial_dependence uses multiprocessing
if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

Discussion¶

The partial dependence plots shows a threshold effect between insulin levels and the pedigree measure. There appears to be a subpopulation of Pima Indian women with a pedigree score higher than .6 with elevated insulin levels who are at greater risk of developing Pre Diabetes than other women in a similar cohort. Further investigation is needed to confirm this finding but if the finding holds it points to an important public health insight: women with a family history of diabetes should have their insulin levels monitored periodically as an early warning of the risk of developing Pre Diabetes.
